NH importance sampler

Introduction

This document contains two main parts

  • uniform and NH approximations
  • A series of solver problems increasing in complexity to find the proper formulation of the NH sampler

28.08.2019

We consider a simple tree with only one branche, and \(T=1\), and we perform samples with both Uniform and Non-homogenous (NH) data augmentation algorithms. For that we use the mc_sample_independent_trees function on the emphasis package.

brts=c(1)
pars = c(2,-0.1,1)
nsim_unif = 1000000
nsim_emph=1000000
st_unif = mc_sample_independent_trees(brts = brts,pars = pars,nsim = nsim_unif,model = "dd",method = "uniform",no_cores = 2,maxnumspec = 10)
st_nh = mc_sample_independent_trees(brts = brts,pars = pars,nsim = nsim_emph,model = "dd",method = "emphasis",no_cores = 2)

The object st_* is a list with all information regarding the simulated set of trees.

We now analize the set of tree by partioning it by dimension (number of missing species). So, the simplest space is the space with zero missing species, which consists on only one tree. We check if the theoritical sampling probability is coherent with the empirical sampling probability. With uniform IS:

#### d = 0

## [1] 0.09090909

With NH IS: #

lambda0 = 2
mu = 1
beta = -0.1
lambda_t <- function(N){lambda0 + beta*N}
b = 1

log_f_one_missing <- function(text,tspe){
  -lambda_t(1) * (tspe-(exp(-b*mu)/mu) *  (exp(tspe*mu)-1)) + log(lambda_t(1)) + log(mu) -mu*text  -2*lambda_t(2) * (text-tspe-(exp(-b*mu)/mu) *  (exp(text*mu)-exp(tspe*mu))) - lambda_t(1) * (b-text-(exp(-b*mu)/mu) * (exp(b*mu)-exp(text*mu)))
}

log_f_one_missing_tspe <- function(tspe){
  int=NULL
  for(i in 1:length(tspe)){
    int[i] = integrate(log_f_one_missing,lower=tspe[i],upper=b,tspe=tspe[i])$value
  }
  return(int)
}

f_one_missing <- function(text,tspe){
  0.95*exp(1.8*(tspe-text)-1.7*(exp(tspe-1)-exp(text-1))+1.9*(-exp(-1)))
}

int_f_one_missing_spe <- function(tspe){
  int=NULL
  for(i in 1:length(tspe)){
    int[i] = integrate(f_one_missing,lower=tspe[i],upper=1,tspe=tspe[i])$value
  }
  return(int)
}

does NHPP simulation do the job?

\[ g(x|y) = \lambda \left( 1-e^{-\mu ( T - t)}\right)e^{-\lambda\int_0^{t^{Sp}} \left( 1-e^{-\mu ( T - t)}\right)dt} \]

log_F_NHPPSpe <- function(t,s,mu,r){
  -s*(t-(exp(-mu*r)/mu)*(exp(mu*t)-1))
}

s = 1.9

now we include extinction

\[ g(x|y) = \lambda \mu e^{-\lambda\int_0^{t^{Sp}} \left( 1-e^{-\mu ( T - t)}\right)dt} e^{-\mu t^{Ex}_{j}} \]

s = 1.9
mu = 1
b = r = 2

nsim = 1000000
rnh=et=NULL
for(i in 1:nsim){
  rnh[i] = rnhpp(s=s,mu=mu,r=b)
  if(rnh[i]<b){
    et[i] = rnh[i] + truncdist::rtrunc(1,"exp",a = 0, b = (b-rnh[i]),rate=mu)
  }else{
    et[i] = Inf
  }
}

f_NHPPSpeExt <- function(tspe,text){
  mu*s*exp(-mu*(text-tspe))*exp(-s*(tspe-(exp(-mu*r)/mu)*(exp(mu*tspe)-1)))
}

Now, we allow multples processes with a step-wise changing rate

\[ g(x|y) = \left[\prod^{p}_{i=1}e^{-\int^{t_{i}}_{t_{i-1}} N_t\lambda_{t} \left( 1-e^{-\mu ( T_{i} -t)}\right) dt} \right] \left[ \prod^{M_{e}}_{j=1} N_{t^{Sp}_j}\lambda_{t^{Sp}_j} \mu e^{-\mu t^{Ex}_{j}} \right] \]

lambda0 = 2
mu = 2
beta = -0.1
lambda_t <- function(N){lambda0 + beta*N}
b = 1

nsim = 1000000
rnh=et=NULL
ct = 0

while(ct<b){
  rnh[i] = rnhpp(s=s,mu=mu,r=b)
  ct = ct + rnh[i]
  if(ct < b){
    et[i] = ct + truncdist::rtrunc(1,"exp",a = 0, b = (b-ct),rate=mu)
  }
}
for(i in 1:nsim){
  rnh[i] = rnhpp(s=s,mu=mu,r=b)
  if(rnh[i]<b){
    et[i] = rnh[i] + truncdist::rtrunc(1,"exp",a = 0, b = (b-rnh[i]),rate=mu)
  }else{
    et[i] = Inf
  }
}

finally, we observe at the whole tree

\[ g(x|y) = \left[\prod^{p}_{i=1}e^{-\int^{t_{i}}_{t_{i-1}} N_t\lambda_{t} \left( 1-e^{-\mu ( T_{i} -t)}\right) dt} \right] \left[ \prod^{M_{e}}_{j=1} \frac{N_{t^{Sp}_j}}{(2N^{o}_{t_j^-}+N^{e}_{t_j^-})}\lambda_{t^{Sp}_j} \mu e^{-\mu t^{Ex}_{j}} \right] \]

On the DD case \(\lambda_t = \lambda_0 + \beta1 N_t\) is constant in the interval \([t_{i-1},t_i]\) for all \(i\). We then have

\[ g(x|y) = \left[\prod^{p}_{i=1}e^{- N_{t_{i-1}}\lambda_{t_{i-1}}\left[t_{i}-t_{i-1}-\frac{e^{-\mu T}}{\mu}(e^{\mu t_i}-e^{\mu t_{i-1}})\right]} \right] \left[ \prod^{M_{e}}_{j=1} \frac{N_{t^{Sp}_j}}{(2N^{o}_{t_j^-}+N^{e}_{t_j^-})}\lambda_{t^{Sp}_j} \mu e^{-\mu t^{Ex}_{j}} \right] \]

or in the logarithm space

\[ \log(g(x|y)) = \left[\sum^{p}_{i=1}- N_{t_{i-1}}\lambda_{t_{i-1}}\left[t_{i}-t_{i-1}-\frac{e^{-\mu T}}{\mu}(e^{\mu t_i}-e^{\mu t_{i-1}})\right] \right] \left[ \sum^{M_{e}}_{j=1} \log{N_{t^{Sp}_j}}-log{(2N^{o}_{t_j^-}+N^{e}_{t_j^-})} +log{\lambda_{t^{Sp}_j}} +\log{\mu} {-\mu t^{Ex}_{j}} \right] \]

with that we can calculate the sampling probability

log_sampling_prob_emphasis <- function(tree,pars,model=NULL,initspec){
  tree = emphasis::df2tree(df=tree,pars,model=model,initspec=initspec)
  wt=tree$wt
  to=tree$to
  n=tree$n
  s=tree$s
  r=tree$r
  t_ext=tree$t_ext
  top_aug=head(tree$treeaug,-1)
  mu = pars[3]
  if(mu!=0){
    sa = s[is.finite(t_ext)]
    text = t_ext[is.finite(t_ext)]
    logg = sum(-s * (wt-(exp(-r*mu)/mu) *  (exp(wt*mu)-1)  ))+sum(is.finite(t_ext))*log(mu)-sum(mu*text)+sum(log(sa))+log.factor.samp.prob_emph(top_aug)
  }else{
    logg = 0
  }
  return(logg)
}

log.factor.samp.prob_emph <- function(to){
  top = head(to,-1)
  number.observed = c(1,1+cumsum(top==2))
  number.missing = c(0,cumsum(top==1)-cumsum(top==0))
  factor = -sum(log((2*number.observed+number.missing)[to==1]))
  return(factor)
}

log_sampling_prob_nh <- function(tree,pars,model=NULL,initspec){
  tree = emphasis::df2tree(df=tree,pars,model=model,initspec=initspec)
  mu = pars[3]
  if(mu!=0){
    sa = s[is.finite(t_ext)]
    text = t_ext[is.finite(t_ext)]
    logg = sum(-s * (wt-(exp(-r*mu)/mu) * (exp(wt*mu)-1)  ))+sum(is.finite(t_ext))*log(mu)-sum(mu*text)+sum(log(sa))+log.factor.samp.prob_emph(top_aug)
  }else{
    logg = 0
  }
  return(logg)
}


log.factor.samp.prob_emph <- function(to){
  top = head(to,-1)
  number.observed = c(1,1+cumsum(top==2))
  number.missing = c(0,cumsum(top==1)-cumsum(top==0))
  factor = -sum(log((2*number.observed+number.missing)[to==1]))
  return(factor)
}
